Irish Crime Statistics

This project is based on the Crimes per Garda Station dataset, which shows the different crimes at each Garda station in Ireland, between the years 2003 and 2016. We chose this dataset, because it is interesting to have a look about crimes tendency during the years in different districts. Comparing crime statistics between garda divisions, we should focus on long-term trends rather than on direct comparison of crime rates of any year, because data may depend on a wide range of factors, such as the effectiveness of Garda work, different peoples social class, demographic, economic, cultural, political situations. In addition, Garda may not record all the crimes. The crime in various ways relates to the social, demographic, economic, legal, political and moral situation of the society, its development and changes. When the countrys situation is strong, the level of crime remains unchanged. Social and economic crisis has a huge impact in periods crime usually increases.

Inferential Statistics

Crimes in Areas - Mateusz Ulinski

Introduction

I will try to answer these three questions:

  • What is the most dangerous area in Ireland? Is there a discrepancy in the crime rates between different areas?
  • Historically, how did the crime in this area change?
  • How do the differnet crimes correlate to eachother, does more of one crime mean more of another?
Method

To answer these questions I will seperate the data into the 4 provinces of Ireland: Leinster, Munster, Ulster and Connacht on which I will conduct various statistics.

The location of the Garda Station is a nominal variable, while all the crime figures are intervals.

We first have to check if there is a discrepancy between the different areas, to do this were going to do a hypothesis test:

H1: There is a discrepancy between the amount of crime in different areas of Ireland H0: There is no discrepancy between the amount of crime in different areas of Ireland

Statistics

Lets take a closer look at our data, first lets get the average number of crimes in each Province in the years between 2003 and 2016:

Crimes Per Province 2003 - 2016
Average Crimes Per Year
Leinster 147403.57
Munster 57803.79
Connacht 20490.93
Ulster 11581.71

From this graph we can understand that over 50% of crimes commited yearly happen in Leinster, this could be due to the population disrecpency between the provinces. So far the data is pointing to rejecting the null hypothesis and accepting that there is a discrepancy between the regions.

Lets see what happens when we normalize the data a bit, using population data from the 2016 census, which is limiting us to only looking at 2016 crime rates. We normalize the data to get a better representation of the crimes, area with less people will naturally have less crime overall, but when you take a look at crimes per person you can get a more accurate picture.

This tells us a bit of a different story, after adjusting for population we can see that Crime per Person in Connacht is a lot higher than in Ulster, while in the unadjusted chart it looked very similar.

From this we can infer that Ulster is the safest province in Ireland, while Leinster and Munster are the most dangerous.

Thus there is indeed discrepancy in crimes between the different regions in Ireland, making us reject the null hypothesis and accept the alternative hypothesis.

We have used a pie chart here to visually represent the proportional difference between crimes in the 4 provinces.

Closer look at Leinster

Let us take a closer look at Leinster, to see how Leinster changed over the years, and which parts are the most dangerous. Were first going to take a look at the Distribution of Crimes between different Garda Divisions in Leinster

From this graph we can clearly see that Dublin North Central had the most crimes in Leinster in 2016, totalling up at 4783! Looking closer at Dublin North Central we can see that it covers the Garda Stations located at Bridewell Dublin, Fitzgibbon Street, Mountjoy, Store Street, these Garda Stations reported the most crime in 2016.

The barplot allows us to visually compare the different divisions in Leinster, easily being able to see how differnet divisions relate to eachother.

Leinster Over The Years

If we take a look at the sum of crimes in Leinster over the years we see that the crime in Leinster peaked in 2008, and slowly went down from there, until it hit the lowest value of 144134 in 2016, a very sharp decrease in reported crime! Explaining the decrease in crime is unfortunately outside the scope of this project.

The line graph here shows us how the crimes have changed in a easy to understand way, up is more, down is less, it is very visually clear to the reader.

Deep into Crime

Here were going to examine how differnet crimes relate to eachother, were going to use Pearsons Correlation Co-Efficient to examine linear relationships between the data.

Lets take a look at a few scatterplots using data from 2016

The scatterplots here show us the correlation of a lot of different variables to eachother, allowing us to quickly judge where a correlation could exist by looking at the chart, which lets us pick the appropriate combinations for further testing.

From looking at the scatterplots we can see that some of our chosen crimes seem to have a correlation with eachother, lets take a closer look at some of them

Drugs and Murder

Judging by the graphs and the Perasons co-efficient, there is a strong positive correlation between the two, meaning that attempts to murder can be linked to the use of drugs.

Burglary and Theft

Looking at Burglary vs Theft, the correlation is weaker than that of Drugs and Murder, there might be some correlation between the two but it is not certian.

We have used the Persons Correlation Co-Efficient here as its a good way to judge the linear relationship of two variables, the higher the P-Value the stronger the correlation is.

Summary

From looking at the data, we have answered the questions:

  • What is the most dangerous area in Ireland? Is there a discrepancy in the crime rates between different areas?
  • Historically, how did the crime in this area change?
  • How do the differnet crimes correlate to eachother, does more of one crime mean more of another?

The most dangerous area in Ireland is Leinster, even after adjusting it for the population difference, historically its been going up in crime until 2008 at which point it peaked and started going down, with an all time low in 2016. We discovered that different crimes correlate to eachother while some dont, Drugs and Murder have a strong correlation while Burlgary and Theft have a weak one, which isnt exactly what you would assume by just thinking about it, but by using data analytics we were able to uncover this information.

The most common crime in Ireland during 2003 and 2016

Looking at the boxplot that I made in The variables in our data section, we can assume that the most common crime is Robbery. In 2016 But is it correlate to other crimes? Lets have a look by comparing.

Pearsons Correlation

library("ggpubr")
## Loading required package: ggplot2
## Loading required package: magrittr
ggscatter(crimes, x='Controlled.drug.offences.2003', y='Controlled.drug.offences.2016.', color='blue', shape = 21, size = 3, conf.int=TRUE, cor.coef = TRUE, cor.method='pearson', add="reg.line", add.params = list(color = "darkgreen", fill = "lightgray"), xlab='Controlled drug offences in 2003', ylab='Controlled drug offences in 2016')

ggscatter(crimes, x='Robbery..extortion.and.hijacking.offences.2003', y='Robbery..extortion.and.hijacking.offences.2016.',color='blue', shape = 21, size = 3, conf.int=TRUE, cor.coef = TRUE, cor.method='pearson', add="reg.line",add.params = list(color = "darkgreen", fill = "lightgray"), xlab="Robbery extortion and hijacking offences in 2003", ylab = "Robbery extortion and hijacking offences in 2016")
